The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems and proposes randomized strategies for solving them. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories related to algorithms and optimization. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is a likely category as the paper proposes approximation algorithms for combinatorial optimization problems. 

cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) is also a likely category as the paper involves an adversary who chooses an objective function, which is a common theme in game theory. 

cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is another possible category as the paper discusses the approximation ratio of the proposed algorithms. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a possible category as the paper uses the multiplicative weights update method, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

cs.IT (Information Theory) is a possible category as the paper introduces a new concept called $(\eta,\gamma)$-reductions, which could be related to information theory.
